BMW, BNP Paribas, Glencore, Rio, RWE: European Equity Preview

-- B y   K a i t l y n   K i e r n a n
-- 
2011-10-10T03:32:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-10/bmw-bnp-paribas-glencore-rio-rwe-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index advanced 0.8 percent to 231.99.
The Stoxx 50 Index rose 0.8 percent to 2,222.32. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark measure for nations using the euro, gained
0.9 percent to 2,269.19.  Banco Pastor SA (PAS)  : Pastor investors Fundacion
Barrie, Amancio Ortega’s Pontegadea Inversiones SL and
Financiere Tesalia SA will present written notification that
they accept Banco Popular’s 1.3 billion-euro ($1.7 billion)
offer for the lender, ABC said, without saying how it obtained
the information.  Bayerische Motoren Werke AG (BMW)  : The world’s biggest
maker of luxury cars will “significantly” exceed its production
target of 1.6 million vehicles this year, Automotive News Europe
reported, citing the company’s head of production, Frank-Peter
Arndt. The shares surged 4.1 percent to 50.89 euros.  BNP Paribas SA (BNP FP) and  Societe Generale (GLE)  SA:
 France ’s largest banks denied a report in Le Journal du Dimanche
that they may seek to raise 7 billion euros ($9.4 billion) and
as much as 4 billion euros respectively to shore up their
capital as part of a Europe-wide plan.  BNP Paribas (BNP)  fell 1.5
percent to 31.55 euros, and Societe Generale dropped 0.9 percent
to 20.51 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : Daimler’s Mercedes-Benz sold 15,272
vehicles in  China  in September, an increase of 12.7 percent from
a year earlier, the official Xinhua News Agency reported. The
stock rose 1.3 percent to 33.98 euros.  Glencore International Plc (GLEN LN): The global
commodities trader may provide a debt facility for PT Bakrie &
Brothers Tbk to help it maintain a 47 percent stake in Bumi Plc,
the Sunday Telegraph reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares fell 2.4 percent to 422 pence.  Henkel AG (HEN3 GY): The maker of glue and detergents may
make acquisitions and could finance the deals from its own
coffers,  Sueddeutsche Zeitung  reported, citing Chief Executive
Officer Kasper Rorsted. The shares slipped 0.1 percent to 41.23
euros.  HSBC Holdings Plc (HSBA)  :  South Korea ’s KDB Financial
Group is interested in taking over HSBC Holdings Plc’s Seoul
branches, MoneyToday reported citing an unidentified official at
KDB.  Kalahari Minerals Plc (KAH)  : China Guangdong Nuclear
Power Group Co. is preparing a 650 million-pound bid for the
U.K.-based uranium miner, the Sunday Times reported, without
saying where it obtained the information. The shares surged 7.2
percent to 246 pence.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO LN): The world’s second-biggest mining
company’s Murowa diamond mine agreed to cede a 51 percent stake
to the Zimbabwean government, the Harare-based Herald reported
today, citing Indigenization Minister  Saviour Kasukuwere . The
stock advanced 1.2 percent to 3,164 pence.  RWE AG (RWE)  :  Germany ’s second-biggest utility may
abandon plans to build atomic power stations in Wales and
 England , the Guardian reported, citing unidentified sources. The
shares gained 1.2 percent to 29.74 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kaitlyn Kiernan in  New York  at 
 kkiernan2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
